{"title_page": "Whitehead's theory of gravitation", "text_new": "In [[theoretical physics]], '''Whitehead's theory of gravitation''' was introduced by the mathematician and philosopher [[Alfred North Whitehead]] in 1922. While never broadly accepted, at one time it was a scientifically plausible [[Alternatives to general relativity|alternative to general relativity]]. However, after further experimental and theoretical consideration, the theory is now generally regarded as obsolete.\n\n==Principal features of the theory==\n[[Clifford M. Will]] argued that Whitehead's theory features a ''prior geometry,''<ref name=Will1972>{{cite journal|last=Will|first=Clifford|title=Einstein on the Firing Line|journal=Physics Today|date=1972|volume=25|issue=10|pages=23\u201329|doi=10.1063/1.3071044|bibcode = 1972PhT....25j..23W }}</ref> but this is disputed by [[Dean R. Fowler]], since it contradicts Whitehead's philosophy of nature. For Whitehead, the geometric structure of nature grows out of the relations among actual occasions. Fowler's interpretation of Whitehead's theory makes it an alternate, mathematically equivalent, presentation of [[general relativity]].<ref name=Fowler>{{cite journal|last=Fowler|first=Dean|title=Disconfirmation of Whitehead's Relativity Theory -- A Critical Reply|journal=Process Studies|date=Winter 1974|volume=4|issue=4|pages=288\u2013290|url=http://www.religion-online.org/showarticle.asp?title=2373|doi=10.5840/process19744432|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108210539/http://www.religion-online.org/showarticle.asp?title=2373|archivedate=2013-01-08}}</ref>\n\nUnder Will's presentation (which was inspired by [[John Lighton Synge]]'s interpretation of the theory<ref>{{cite book|last=Synge|first=John|title=Relativity Theory of A. N. Whitehead|date=1951|publisher=University of Maryland|location=Baltimore}}</ref><ref name=Tanaka>{{cite journal|last=Tanaka|first=Yutaka|title=Einstein and Whitehead-The Comparison between Einstein's and Whitehead's Theories of Relativity|journal=Historia Scientiarum|date=1987|volume=32|url=http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/process/society/tanaka_4_0.htm}}</ref>), Whitehead's theory has the curious feature that electromagnetic waves propagate along [[null geodesic]]s of the physical [[spacetime]] (as defined by the [[metric tensor|metric]] determined from geometrical measurements and timing experiments), while gravitational waves propagate along null geodesics of a ''flat background'' represented by the metric tensor of [[Minkowski spacetime]]. The gravitational potential can be expressed entirely in terms of waves retarded along the background metric, like the [[Li\u00e9nard\u2013Wiechert potential]] in electromagnetic theory.\n\nA [[cosmological constant]] can be introduced by changing the background metric to a [[de Sitter space|de Sitter]] or [[anti-de Sitter space|anti-de Sitter]] metric. This was first suggested by G. Temple in 1923.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Temple|first=G.|title=Central Orbit in Relativistic Dynamics Treated by the Hamilton-Jacobi Method|journal=Philosophical Magazine|date=1924|volume=48|issue=284|series=6|pages=277\u2013292|doi=10.1080/14786442408634491}}</ref>  Temple's suggestions on how to do this were criticized by C. B. Rayner in 1955.<ref name=Rayner1954>{{cite journal|last=Rayner|first=C.|title=The Application of the Whitehead Theory of Relativity to Non-static Spherically Symmetrical Systems|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London|date=1954|volume=222|issue=1151|pages=509\u2013526|doi=10.1098/rspa.1954.0092|bibcode = 1954RSPSA.222..509R }}</ref><ref name=Rayner1955>{{cite journal|last=Rayner|first=C.|title=The Effects of Rotation in the Central Body on its Planetary Orbits after the Whitehead Theory of Gravitation|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London|date=1955|volume=232|issue=1188|pages=135\u2013148|doi=10.1098/rspa.1955.0206|bibcode = 1955RSPSA.232..135R }}</ref>\n\n==Tests of Whitehead's theory==\nWhitehead's theory is equivalent with the [[Schwarzschild metric]]<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Eddington | first1 = A.S. | year = 1924 | title = A comparison of Whitehead's and Einstein's formulas | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 113 | issue = 2832| page = 192 | doi=10.1038/113192a0|bibcode = 1924Natur.113..192E }}</ref> and makes the same predictions as general relativity regarding the [[:Category:Tests of general relativity|four classical solar system tests]] ([[gravitational red shift]], light bending, [[perihelion]] shift, [[Shapiro delay|Shapiro time delay]]), and was regarded as a viable competitor of general relativity for several decades. In 1971, young [[Clifford Martin Will|Clifford M. Will]] thanks [[Ni Wei-Tou|Ni Wei-To]] to comprehend Whitehead's theory<ref>{{cite journal | last=Will | first=Clifford M. | title=Relativistic Gravity in the Solar System. II. Anisotropy in the Newtonian Gravitational Constant | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | publisher=IOP Publishing | volume=169 | year=1971 | issn=0004-637X | doi=10.1086/151125 | page=141|bibcode=1971ApJ...169..141W}}</ref> and claims that the theory makes predictions concerning ordinary [[physical oceanography|ocean tides]] on Earth (suggested to him by [[Jim Peebles]]) which are in violent disagreement with observation (specifically, the theory predicts a \"sidereal tide\", induced by the gravitational field of the Milky Way, which is hundreds of times stronger than the solar and lunar tides) which immediately nullified this theory.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Gibbons | first=Gary | last2=Will | first2=Clifford M. | title=On the multiple deaths of Whitehead's theory of gravity | journal=Studies in History and Philosophy of Science Part B: Studies in History and Philosophy of Modern Physics | publisher=Elsevier BV | volume=39 | issue=1 | year=2008 | issn=1355-2198 | doi=10.1016/j.shpsb.2007.04.004 | pages=41\u201361|arxiv=gr-qc/0611006}}</ref> As mentioned previously, the interpretation of the theory used by Will has been criticized by Fowler, who has also argued that different tidal predictions can be obtained by a more realistic model of the galaxy.<ref name=Fowler/><ref name=Bain>{{cite journal|last=Bain|first=Jonathan|title=Whitehead's Theory of Gravity|journal=Stud. Hist. Phil. Mod. Phys.|date=1998|volume=29|issue=4|pages=547\u2013574|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/72164387/WhiteheadsTheoryofGravity-Bain|doi=10.1016/s1355-2198(98)00022-7|bibcode=1998SHPMP..29..547B}}</ref> Also Reinhardt and Rosenblum criticised such statements.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Reinhardt | first=M. | last2=Rosenblum | first2=A. | title=Whitehead contra Einstein | journal=Physics Letters A | publisher=Elsevier BV | volume=48 | issue=2 | year=1974 | issn=0375-9601 | doi=10.1016/0375-9601(74)90425-3 | pages=115\u2013116}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, a new interpretation of Whitehead's theory was proposed that eliminated the unobserved sidereal tide effects.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Hyman | first1 = Andrew | year = 1989 |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120204224955/http://www.andrewhyman.com/articles/whitehead.pdf | title =A New Interpretation of Whitehead's Theory]\", 104B | journal = Il Nuovo Cimento | volume = 387 | issue = 4| pages = 387\u2013398| doi=10.1007/bf02725671|bibcode = 1989NCimB.104..387H }}</ref>  However, the new interpretation predicted a new, unobserved, effect, called the \"[[Nordtvedt effect]].\"{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alfred North Whitehead]]\n*[[Classical theories of gravitation]]\n*[[Eddington\u2013Finkelstein coordinates]]\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book | author=Will, Clifford M. | title=Was Einstein Right?: Putting General Relativity to the Test  | edition=2nd | publisher=[[Basic Books]] | date=1993 | isbn=978-0-465-09086-0}}\n*{{cite book | author=Misner, Charles | author2=Thorne, Kip S. | author3=Wheeler, John Archibald | last-author-amp=yes | title=Gravitation | location=San Francisco | publisher=W. H. Freeman | date=1973 | isbn=978-0-7167-0344-0}} discusses Whitehead's theory in various places.\n\n{{theories of gravitation}}\n\n[[Category:Alfred North Whitehead]]\n[[Category:Obsolete scientific theories]]\n[[Category:Theories of gravitation]]\n", "text_old": "In [[theoretical physics]], '''Whitehead's theory of gravitation''' was introduced by the mathematician and philosopher [[Alfred North Whitehead]] in 1922. While never broadly accepted, at one time it was a scientifically plausible [[Alternatives to general relativity|alternative to general relativity]]. However, after further experimental and theoretical consideration, the theory is now generally regarded as obsolete.\n\n==Principal features of the theory==\n[[Clifford M. Will]] argued that Whitehead's theory features a ''prior geometry,''<ref name=Will1972>{{cite journal|last=Will|first=Clifford|title=Einstein on the Firing Line|journal=Physics Today|date=1972|volume=25|issue=10|pages=23\u201329|doi=10.1063/1.3071044|bibcode = 1972PhT....25j..23W }}</ref> but this is disputed by [[Dean R. Fowler]], since it contradicts Whitehead's philosophy of nature. For Whitehead, the geometric structure of nature grows out of the relations among actual occasions. Fowler's interpretation of Whitehead's theory makes it an alternate, mathematically equivalent, presentation of [[general relativity]].<ref name=Fowler>{{cite journal|last=Fowler|first=Dean|title=Disconfirmation of Whitehead's Relativity Theory -- A Critical Reply|journal=Process Studies|date=Winter 1974|volume=4|issue=4|pages=288\u2013290|url=http://www.religion-online.org/showarticle.asp?title=2373|doi=10.5840/process19744432|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108210539/http://www.religion-online.org/showarticle.asp?title=2373|archivedate=2013-01-08}}</ref>\n\nUnder Will's presentation (which was inspired by [[John Lighton Synge]]'s interpretation of the theory<ref>{{cite book|last=Synge|first=John|title=Relativity Theory of A. N. Whitehead|date=1951|publisher=University of Maryland|location=Baltimore}}</ref><ref name=Tanaka>{{cite journal|last=Tanaka|first=Yutaka|title=Einstein and Whitehead-The Comparison between Einstein's and Whitehead's Theories of Relativity|journal=Historia Scientiarum|date=1987|volume=32|url=http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/process/society/tanaka_4_0.htm}}</ref>), Whitehead's theory has the curious feature that electromagnetic waves propagate along [[null geodesic]]s of the physical [[spacetime]] (as defined by the [[metric tensor|metric]] determined from geometrical measurements and timing experiments), while gravitational waves propagate along null geodesics of a ''flat background'' represented by the metric tensor of [[Minkowski spacetime]]. The gravitational potential can be expressed entirely in terms of waves retarded along the background metric, like the [[Li\u00e9nard\u2013Wiechert potential]] in electromagnetic theory.\n\nA [[cosmological constant]] can be introduced by changing the background metric to a [[de Sitter space|de Sitter]] or [[anti-de Sitter space|anti-de Sitter]] metric. This was first suggested by G. Temple in 1923.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Temple|first=G.|title=Central Orbit in Relativistic Dynamics Treated by the Hamilton-Jacobi Method|journal=Philosophical Magazine|date=1924|volume=48|issue=284|series=6|pages=277\u2013292|doi=10.1080/14786442408634491}}</ref>  Temple's suggestions on how to do this were criticized by C. B. Rayner in 1955.<ref name=Rayner1954>{{cite journal|last=Rayner|first=C.|title=The Application of the Whitehead Theory of Relativity to Non-static Spherically Symmetrical Systems|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London|date=1954|volume=222|issue=1151|pages=509\u2013526|doi=10.1098/rspa.1954.0092|bibcode = 1954RSPSA.222..509R }}</ref><ref name=Rayner1955>{{cite journal|last=Rayner|first=C.|title=The Effects of Rotation in the Central Body on its Planetary Orbits after the Whitehead Theory of Gravitation|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London|date=1955|volume=232|issue=1188|pages=135\u2013148|doi=10.1098/rspa.1955.0206|bibcode = 1955RSPSA.232..135R }}</ref>\n\n==Tests of Whitehead's theory==\nWhitehead's theory is equivalent with the [[Schwarzschild metric]]<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Eddington | first1 = A.S. | year = 1924 | title = A comparison of Whitehead's and Einstein's formulas | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 113 | issue = 2832| page = 192 | doi=10.1038/113192a0|bibcode = 1924Natur.113..192E }}</ref> and makes the same predictions as general relativity regarding the [[:Category:Tests of general relativity|four classical solar system tests]] ([[gravitational red shift]], light bending, [[perihelion]] shift, [[Shapiro delay|Shapiro time delay]]), and was regarded as a viable competitor of general relativity for several decades. In 1971, young [[Clifford Martin Will|Clifford M. Will]] thanks [[Ni Wei-Tou|Ni Wei-To]] to comprehend Whitehead's theory<ref>{{cite journal | last=Will | first=Clifford M. | title=Relativistic Gravity in the Solar System. II. Anisotropy in the Newtonian Gravitational Constant | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | publisher=IOP Publishing | volume=169 | year=1971 | issn=0004-637X | doi=10.1086/151125 | page=141|bibcode=1971ApJ...169..141W}}</ref> and claims that the theory makes predictions concerning ordinary [[physical oceanography|ocean tides]] on Earth (suggested to him by [[Jim Peebles]]) which are in violent disagreement with observation (specifically, the theory predicts a \"sidereal tide\", induced by the gravitational field of the Milky Way, which is hundreds of times stronger than the solar and lunar tides) which immediately nullified this theory.<ref>Will, Clifford & Gibbons, Gary. \"[https://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0611006 On the Multiple Deaths of Whitehead's Theory of Gravity]\", to be submitted to ''Studies In History And Philosophy Of Modern Physics'' (2006).</ref> As mentioned previously, the interpretation of the theory used by Will has been criticized by Fowler, who has also argued that different tidal predictions can be obtained by a more realistic model of the galaxy.<ref name=Fowler/><ref name=Bain>{{cite journal|last=Bain|first=Jonathan|title=Whitehead's Theory of Gravity|journal=Stud. Hist. Phil. Mod. Phys.|date=1998|volume=29|issue=4|pages=547\u2013574|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/72164387/WhiteheadsTheoryofGravity-Bain|doi=10.1016/s1355-2198(98)00022-7|bibcode=1998SHPMP..29..547B}}</ref> Also Reinhardt and Rosenblum criticised such statements.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Reinhardt | first=M. | last2=Rosenblum | first2=A. | title=Whitehead contra Einstein | journal=Physics Letters A | publisher=Elsevier BV | volume=48 | issue=2 | year=1974 | issn=0375-9601 | doi=10.1016/0375-9601(74)90425-3 | pages=115\u2013116}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, a new interpretation of Whitehead's theory was proposed that eliminated the unobserved sidereal tide effects.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Hyman | first1 = Andrew | year = 1989 |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120204224955/http://www.andrewhyman.com/articles/whitehead.pdf | title =A New Interpretation of Whitehead's Theory]\", 104B | journal = Il Nuovo Cimento | volume = 387 | issue = 4| pages = 387\u2013398| doi=10.1007/bf02725671|bibcode = 1989NCimB.104..387H }}</ref>  However, the new interpretation predicted a new, unobserved, effect, called the \"[[Nordtvedt effect]].\"{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alfred North Whitehead]]\n*[[Classical theories of gravitation]]\n*[[Eddington\u2013Finkelstein coordinates]]\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book | author=Will, Clifford M. | title=Was Einstein Right?: Putting General Relativity to the Test  | edition=2nd | publisher=[[Basic Books]] | date=1993 | isbn=978-0-465-09086-0}}\n*{{cite book | author=Misner, Charles | author2=Thorne, Kip S. | author3=Wheeler, John Archibald | last-author-amp=yes | title=Gravitation | location=San Francisco | publisher=W.